Feature: a running spike's scratch infra is isolated and disposable, and nothing is committed to lead or BC source

  Lifecycle stage 3 (Throwaway execution) — ADR-030 D1/D2/D3, PDR-016 capability
  point 3. A spike stands up real infra in isolated scratch: `spike-`-prefixed
  containers on the real network with dummy/placeholder data only, and `/tmp` or a
  throwaway worktree branch for code. The live fleet and real credentials are never
  touched, and nothing from scratch is ever committed to lead or BC source. This is
  a LEAD-PROCESS behavior: spike scratch is lead-host infra (the narrow carve-out to
  the "no implementation code in the lead repo" rule), not BC-owned; there is no BC
  addressee. The `spike-` prefix is the observable, mechanically-auditable isolation
  contract.

@scenario_hash:09b6737899fed349 @lead_integration:spike-lifecycle
  Scenario: a running spike uses spike-prefixed scratch with dummy data and commits nothing to lead or BC source
    Given a spike in throwaway execution that has stood up real infra to exercise its assertions
    When the spike's scratch infra is inspected during execution
    Then every container the spike stood up is named with a "spike-" prefix on the real network
    And the spike's infra holds only dummy or placeholder data, with the live fleet and real credentials untouched
    And nothing from the spike's scratch is committed to lead or BC source
